<chapter xml:id="CHAPTERPFDTheory" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The  Theory Behind the  Partial Fraction Decomposition  </title>

  <p>
    Previously, we provided a number of ways to compute the
    coefficients in the partial fractions decomposition of a rational
    function.  In all those instances, we assumed that a rational
    function had such a decomposition.  The fact that there is a
    partial fractions decomposition is actually an algebraic result
    not a calculus one, but we will provide some rationale as to why
    this is true.  Let's start with something relatively easy to see
    where the ideas come from.
  </p>

  <p>
    Suppose <m>a,b</m> are two distinct numbers.  Then
    <me>\left(x-b\right)-\left(x-a\right)=a-b</me> 
    so
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFD2">
      \left(\frac{1}{a-b}\right)\left(x-b\right)+\left(\frac{1}{b-a}\right)\left(x-a\right)=1
    </men>
    and finally
    <me>
    \frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}=\frac{\left(\frac{1}{a-b}\right)\left(x-b\right)+\left(\frac{1}{b-a}\right)\left(x-a\right)}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}=\frac{\left(\frac{1}{a-b}\right)}{x-a}+\frac{\left(\frac{1}{b-a}\right)}{x-b}
    </me> 
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="EQUATIONPFD2">Equation</xref> is a special case of a
      more general fact stated below:
    </p>

    <p>
      Given two polynomials <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> with no common
      factors (except trivial ones such as constants), then there are
      polynomials <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> such that
    </p>
      
    <p>
      <me>r\left(x\right)p\left(x\right)+s\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)=1</me> 
    </p>
    <p>
      It should be noted that having no common non<ndash/>trivial factors is
      the equivalent to having no common roots (real or complex).  We
      will not prove this result here, but we will note that its
      derivation is exactly the same as the following number theory
      result (which we will not prove either).
    </p>

    <p>
      Let <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> be two positive integers with
      <m>{\mathrm{gcd} (p,q) }=1</m> [i.e.: <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>
      have no common factors, except for the trivial factor 1].  Then
      there exist integers <m>r, s</m> with <me>r\cdot p+s\cdot
      q=1</me>
    </p>

    <p>
      As an example, notice that <m>{\mathrm{gcd} \left(9, \
      7\right)=1 }</m>, and so <m>-3\cdot 9+4\cdot 7=1</m>.  There is
      a systematic way to find the integers <m>r, s</m> (and
      analogously, the polynomials <m>r\left(x\right), s(x)</m>) in
      general, but we will just use the fact that these exist for our
      purposes.  With the above polynomial result in place, we can
      manipulate as we did above

      <me>1=r\left(x\right)p\left(x\right)+s\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)</me> 

      <me>\frac{1}{p\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)}=\frac{r\left(x\right)p\left(x\right)+s\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)}{p\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)}=\frac{s\left(x\right)}{p\left(x\right)}+\frac{r\left(x\right)}{q\left(x\right)}</me> 
      </p>
      <p>


        Thus if <m>f(x)</m> is any polynomial, then we have

          
        <me>\frac{f(x)}{p\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)}=\frac{f(x)s\left(x\right)}{p\left(x\right)}+\frac{f(x)r\left(x\right)}{q\left(x\right)}</me> 
        </p>

        <p>
          This says that our goal of finding a partial fractions
          decomposition is theoretically possible.  Before we make our
          <q>educated guess</q> as to what the numerators will look
          like, we will make an observation that might make our guess
          even more educated and narrow our search.
        </p>

        <p>
          Observation: Notice that if the degree of <m>f(x)</m> is
          less than the degree of <m>p\left(x\right)q(x)</m>, then we
          can assume that the degree of the numerators in the partial
          fractions will be less than the degrees of the denominators.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you think about this, it makes sense.  First, we should
          point out that the numerators in the partial fractions are
          not unique, but there is no sense introducing higher degree
          terms in the numerators that would just cancel out anyway
          when these fractions are combined.  For example, if we had

            
          <me>\frac{3x-4}{\left(x-1\right)\left(x+2\right)}=\frac{ax+b}{x-1}+\frac{cx+d}{x+2}</me> 
          then
            
          <me>\frac{3x-4}{\left(x-1\right)\left(x+2\right)}=\frac{\left(ax+b\right)\left(x+2\right)+(cx+d)(x-1)}{\left(x-1\right)\left(x+2\right)}=\frac{\left(a+c\right)x^2+\left(2a+b-c+d\right)x+(2b-d)}{\left(x-1\right)\left(x+2\right)}</me> 
          </p>

          <p>
            We might as well assume that <m>a=c=0</m> and try to find <m>b, d</m> such that 

            <me>3x-4=\left(b+d\right)x+(2b-d)</me> 
          </p>

          <p>
            Again, we want to point out that this is not necessary,
            but it makes for a more <q>educated</q> guess and cuts out
            some unnecessary work.
          </p>
              
          <p>
            The same ideas can be extended if we have three or more
            polynomials in the denominator which pairwise have no
            non<ndash/>trivial factors.
          </p>

          <theorem xml:id="THEOREMPFDThreeFactor">
            <title>The PFD with Three Factors</title>
            <p>
              Suppose we have three polynomials
              <m>n\left(x\right),p\left(x\right), q\left(x\right)</m>
              which pairwise have no non-trivial common factors.  Then
              there exist polynomials
              <m>r\left(x\right),s\left(x\right),t(x)</m> with
              <me>\frac{1}{n\left(x\right)\cdot p\left(x\right)\cdot
              q(x)}=\frac{r\left(x\right)}{n\left(x\right)}+\frac{s\left(x\right)}{p\left(x\right)}+\frac{t\left(x\right)}{q\left(x\right)}</me>
            </p>
          </theorem>


          <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPFDThreeFactor">

            <statement>
              <p>
                Prove Theorem <xref ref="THEOREMPFDThreeFactor"></xref>.
              </p>

            </statement>
            <hint>
              <p>
                We can write <m>\frac{1}{n\left(x\right)\cdot p\left(x\right)\cdot q(x)}=\frac{r\left(x\right)}{n\left(x\right)}+\frac{m\left(x\right)}{p\left(x\right)\cdot q(x)}=\frac{r\left(x\right)}{n\left(x\right)}+m\left(x\right)\left(\frac{1}{p\left(x\right)\cdot q\left(x\right)}\right)</m> for some polynomials <m>r\left(x\right), m(x)</m>.
              </p>
            </hint>
          </exercise>

          <p>
            Since the goal in a partial fractions decomposition is
            to split a rational function into as many <q>simpler</q>
            pieces as possible, we will explore what can happen.
            We will use specific examples to illustrate these
            situations, but the ideas involved apply in general.
          </p>

          <p>
            We already took care of the case where we have
            distinct linear factors.  What if we have a factor
            which is repeated.  For example, suppose we have
            <me>\frac{1}{x^3\left(x-1\right)}</me> 
          </p>

          <p>
            Since <m>x^3</m> and <m>3x-1</m> have no non trivial common factors, then we already know we can write
            <me>\frac{1}{x^3\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{Ax^2+Bx+C}{x^3}+\frac{D}{x-1}</me> 
            where the constants <m>A,B,C,D</m> need to be determined by one of the methods we employed before.  Of course, this can be rewritten as
            <me>\frac{1}{x^3\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{A}{x}+\frac{B}{x^2}+\frac{C}{x^3}+\frac{D}{x-1}</me> 

            which represents our partial fractions decomposition.
          </p>

                <p>
                  We can employ a similar idea if we have something like <m>\frac{1}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3\left(x-1\right)}</m>
                </p>

                <p>
                  In this case we have
                    
                  <me>\frac{1}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{Ax^2+Bx+C}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3}+\frac{D}{x-1}</me>. 
                </p>

                <p>
                  If we rewrite this as
                    
                  <me>\frac{1}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{A{[\left(x+1)-1\right]}^2+B[\left(x+1\right)-1]+C}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3}+\frac{D}{x-1}</me> 
                  <me>=\frac{{A\left(x+1\right)}^2-2A\left(x+1\right)+A+B\left(x+1\right)-B+C}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3}+\frac{D}{x-1}</me> 
                  <me>=\frac{A}{x+1}+\frac{-2A+B}{{\left(x+1\right)}^2}+\frac{-2A-B+C}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3}+\frac{D}{x-1}</me> 
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    If we relabel things, we get our partial fractions decomposition
                    <me>\frac{1}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{A}{x+1}+\frac{B}{{\left(x+1\right)}^2}+\frac{C}{{\left(x+1\right)}^3}+\frac{D}{x-1}</me> 
                    where <m>A,B,C,D</m> are constants that need to be determined using methods we learned before.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Suppose our repeated factor is not linear, say we had <m>\frac{1}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2x}</m>.  By our general result above, we have

                      <me>\frac{1}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2x}=\frac{Ax^3+Bx^2+Cx+D}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2}+\frac{E}{x}</me> 
                    </p>

                    <p>
                      Employing a similar trick to what we did with a repeated linear factor, we have

                        
                      <me>\frac{1}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2x}=\frac{A\left(x^3+x\right)+B\left(x^2+1\right)+Cx-Ax-B+D}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2}+\frac{E}{x}</me> 
                      <me>=\frac{Ax\left(x^2+1\right)+B\left(x^2+1\right)+\left(C-A\right)x+D-B}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2}+\frac{E}{x}</me> 
                      <me>=\frac{Ax+B}{x^2+1}+\frac{\left(C-A\right)x+D-B}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2}+\frac{E}{x}</me> 
                      </p>

                      <p>
                        Relabeling, we have our partial fractions decomposition
                      </p>

                      <p>
                        <me>\frac{1}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2x}=\frac{Ax+B}{x^2+1}+\frac{Cx+D}{{\left(x^2+1\right)}^2}+\frac{E}{x}</me> 

                        where the coefficients <m>A,B,C,D,E</m> can be
                        determined by one of our previous methods.
                      </p>

                        <p>
                          We will stop at linear and quadratic factors
                          even though the ideas we just illustrated
                          would work for them as well.  The fact is
                          that any polynomial of degree three or
                          higher can be factored into two or more
                          other polynomials of lesser degree.  This
                          says that linear and quadratic factors are
                          the only possible irreducible factors.  The
                          reason that this is true follows by
                          extending our roots to complex numbers as
                          well.  There are a couple of reasons for
                          doing this.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                          First: The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra,
                          says that any polynomial <m>q(x)</m> with
                          real coefficients can factored into the form
                          <m>q\left(x\right)=a_n\left(x-r_1\right)\left(x-r_2\right)\cdots
                          \left(x-r_n\right)</m> where
                          <m>r_1,r_2,\dots ,r_n</m> are the (possibly
                          complex) roots of <m>q(x)</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                          Second: If <m>r=a+bi</m> is a root of
                          <m>q(x)</m> then its complex conjugate
                          <m>\overline{r}=a-bi</m> is also a root.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                          When we multiply two such linear factors together, we have
                          <me>\left(x-\left(a+bi\right)\right)\left(x-\left(a-bi\right)\right)=x^2-2ax+(a^2+b^2)</me> 
                          which is a quadratic factor with real coefficients.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                          The upshot of all this is that if we want to
                          find the partial fractions decomposition of
                          a rational function
                          <m>\frac{p\left(x\right)}{q\left(x\right)}</m>,
                          we do the following:
                        </p>
                        <algorithm xml:id="ALGORITHMPFD">
                          <title>The Partial Fraction Decomposition</title>
                          <p>
                            <ol  marker="(1)">
                              <li>
                                Use long division to ensure that the
                                degree of the numerator is less than the
                                degree of the denominator.
                              </li>
                              <li>
                                Factor the denominator completely (over
                                the real numbers).  These irreducible
                                factors will either be linear or
                                quadratic.
                              </li>
                              <li>
                                For any linear factor of the form
                                <m>{\left(ax+b\right)}^n</m>, form the
                                sum
                                <me>\frac{A_1}{ax+b}+\frac{A_2}{{\left(ax+b\right)}^2}+\dots
                                +\frac{A_n}{{\left(ax+b\right)}^n}</me>
                              </li>
                              <li>
                                For any quadratic factor of the form
                                <m>{\left(ax^2+bx+c\right)}^m</m>, form
                                the sum
                                <me>\frac{B_1x+C_1}{ax^2+bx+c}+\frac{B_2x+C_2}{{\left(ax^2+bx+c\right)}^2}+\dots
                                +\frac{B_mx+C_m}{{\left(ax^2+bx+c\right)}^m}</me>
                              </li>
                              <li>
                                Find all the coefficients using one of
                                the methods we employed before.
                              </li>
                            </ol>

</p>
                        </algorithm>


                        <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPFDBig">
                          <introduction>
                            <p>
                              Write down the form of the partial fractions decomposition for each of the following rational functions.  DO NOT TRY TO DETERMINE THE COEFFICIENTS (unless you have nothing better to do)!
                            </p>
                          </introduction>
                          <task>
                            <statement>
                              <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle\frac{1}{\left(3x+1\right)\left(x-2\right)}</m> 
                              </p>
                            </statement>
                          </task>
                          <task>
                            <statement>
                              <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle\frac{2x-1}{{\left(x^2+x+1\right)}^3{\left(5x-4\right)}^2}</m> 
                              </p>
                            </statement>
                          </task>
                          <task>
                            <statement>
                              <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle\frac{x^4}{\left(x^2+1\right){\left(x-1\right)}^2}</m> 
                              </p>
                            </statement>
                          </task>
                        </exercise>

